docs.abstract: Mark-Anthony Turnage’s raucous “Greek,” which moves Sophocles forward to an unsettled contemporary London, comes to the Brooklyn Academy of Music.
docs.snippet: Mark-Anthony Turnage’s raucous “Greek,” which moves Sophocles forward to an unsettled contemporary London, comes to the Brooklyn Academy of Music.
docs.lead_paragraph: LONDON — Oedipus is wearing a bright red tracksuit. His parents, brandishing beer bottles, are off to the pub to watch a football match. “So, I was born in Tufnell Park,” he says aggressively to the audience, adding: “It’s a cesspit!”

headline.main: The Orchestra Brawls in a ‘Beer and Pizza’ Oedipus Opera
headline.print_headline: In an Oedipal Opera, Londoners Chant, Curse and Brawl

docs.abstract: She and political strategists like Jessica Byrd and Kayla Reed are designing a new theory of the Democratic coalition.
docs.snippet: She and political strategists like Jessica Byrd and Kayla Reed are designing a new theory of the Democratic coalition.
docs.lead_paragraph: For too long, the Democratic Party has been comfortable with black women only running conventions or registering voters — doing background work. The party expects black women to be its backbone, as when 98 percent of black female voters in Alabama cast their ballots for Doug Jones in the special Senate election last year. But it has never truly supported them as leaders.

headline.main: Stacey Abrams and the Black Women Reshaping the Left

docs.snippet: Our critics select museum and gallery exhibitions that provide a respite from carols and crowds.
docs.lead_paragraph: In her career survey, “Image of an Image,” Rochelle Feinstein, a Bronx native, proves that she can do just about anything with painting. She can chronicle history or tell a joke. She can alchemize linen, photographs, newspapers, cardboard and photocopies into art. She can teach you something about looking and life. (Until recently, Ms. Feinstein was a professor of painting at Yale.)

headline.main: 10 Under-the-Radar Art Shows to See Now

docs.abstract: How the Pop master’s experimentation helped them find their own voice.
docs.snippet: How the Pop master’s experimentation helped them find their own voice.
docs.lead_paragraph: Three decades after Andy Warhol’s death, he remains one of America’s most provocative artists. His influence on popular culture is so pervasive that each emerging art movement after him has had to grapple with Warhol’s focus on surface perfections and his singular celebrity.   Despite their complicated feelings, many contemporary artists say they continue to admire Warhol’s radical experimentation in all media and reach back to him as an unflagging inspiration, citing his practice of fusing photography and painting, as well as his presentations of race, gender, religion and desire.

headline.main: Seven Artists on the Warhol Influence
headline.print_headline: His Example  Helped Them  Find a Voice
